Preparing the Manaus data for Kaplan Meier curves¶

Notes:

  • In a standard survival analysis with censored observations, once we censor a subject at a given time, we know for a fact he/she did not experience the event at that time (i.e.: that was the last known time that individual was alive).
  • In SIVEP-Gripe we have right-censoring of outcomes, but that does not mean they are known to be alive. Thye could be either dead or alive, and thus these censored observations cannot be relied upon.
  • I have chosen to determine a cutoff for analysis that is long enough in the past that it allows a reasonable time for outcomes field to be filled in. Any records with missing data are simply excluded. This might affect results. Steps:
  1. Calculate the following intervals:
    • Onset of Symptoms to Hospital Admission
    • Onset of Symptoms to Death (or Hospital Discharge)
    • Hospital Admission to Death (or Hospital Discharge)
    • Age at notification
  2. Create event columns with 0/1 responses for the following:
    • Death
    • Hospitalization
  3. Exclude all records that were notified less than 10 weeks before the most recent SIVEP release
    • This should be enough to allow for sufficient time for hospital treatment to have happened and records updated.
  4. Exclude all records with missing data for final outcome (EVOLUCAO and DT_EVOLUCA cannot be NaN)
  5. Select only records that were notified in Amazonas (SG_UF_NOT == 'AM'). This should include both hospitalized and non hospitalized records, but non-hospitalized records will be excluded at the point of analysis.
In [1630]:
### STEP 1
### Calculate Intervals

## Time from Onset of Symptoms to Hospital Admission
df['Onset_to_Hosp'] = (df['DT_INTERNA'] - df['DT_SIN_PRI']).dt.days

## Time from Onset of Symptoms to Death or Discharge
df['Onset_to_Evolucao'] = (df['DT_EVOLUCA'] - df['DT_SIN_PRI']).dt.days

## Time from Hospital Admission to Death or Discharge
df['Hosp_to_Evolucao'] = (df['DT_EVOLUCA'] - df['DT_INTERNA']).dt.days

## Age at date of notification
df['Age'] = (df['DT_NOTIFIC'] - df['DT_NASC']).dt.days / 365.25 #This results in a datetime object representing age in years
df['Age'] = df['Age'].fillna(0).astype('int') # Converts from datetime to int
In [1631]:
### STEP 2
### Create the event columns

df.loc[(df['EVOLUCAO'] == '2'), 'Death'] = 1 # Creates the 'Death' column and assigns the value '1' to all records that died
df['Death'] = df['Death'].fillna(0) # By logic, all records that have missing data on this field did not have a clearly recorded death event, and thus should be filled with '0'

df.loc[(df['HOSPITAL'] == '1'), 'Hospitalization'] = 1 # Creates the 'Hospitalization' column and assigns the value '1' to all records that were indeed hospitalized
df['Hospitalization'] = df['Hospitalization'].fillna(0) # By logic, all records that have missing data on this field did not have a clearly recorded hospitalization event, and thus should be filled with '0'

Out of Hospital Deaths¶

Scraped from online Tableau published by Amazonas Health Department:
https://public.tableau.com/views/MonitoramentoSepultamentos/Obtdomiclio

A baseline interwave period is defined between 01 July 2020 and 01 December 2020
Mean and 95% Confidence Interval is calculated for this period

Excess Out of Hospital Deaths are calculated by two different methods:

  • Conservatively: by subtracting the upper bound of the 95%CI from the total number of out of hospital deaths for that week
  • Less conservatively: by subtracting the mean from the total number of out of hospital deaths for that week
In [1636]:
### Load Out of Hospital Deaths Information
home_deaths = pd.read_csv('../data/Manaus.OutOfHospitalDeaths-Daily.csv',parse_dates=['Date'], index_col='Date')

# Period of low disease activity to be used as a baseline for excess all-cause out of hospital deaths
# Looking at the plot I chose 01 July 2020 to 01 December 2020
quiet_period = home_deaths.loc[(home_deaths.index > '2020-07-01') & (home_deaths.index < '2020-12-01') , 'Total' ]

## Calculates the 95% CIs for this data
ci_OuH_deaths = st.norm.interval(0.95, loc=np.mean(quiet_period), scale=np.std(quiet_period))

## Calculates the excess weekly out of hospital deaths by subtracting the actual value from the upper boundary of the 99% CI
home_deaths['ExcessHomeDeaths_CI'] = home_deaths['Total'] - ci_OuH_deaths[1]
home_deaths['ExcessHomeDeaths_Mean'] = home_deaths['Total'] - quiet_period.mean()

home_deaths.loc[home_deaths['ExcessHomeDeaths_CI'] < 0, 'ExcessHomeDeaths_CI'] = 0 # Assigns all negative excess to zero. I don't see a reason why negative excess burials would have significance to COVID mortality
home_deaths.loc[home_deaths['ExcessHomeDeaths_Mean'] < 0, 'ExcessHomeDeaths_Mean'] = 0 

print('Interwave Weekly Out of Hospital Deaths Mean: ',quiet_period.mean())
print('Interwave Weekly Out of Hospital Deaths Median: ',quiet_period.median())
print('Interwave Weekly Out of Hospital Deaths 95% CI: ',ci_OuH_deaths)

Interwave Weekly Out of Hospital Deaths Median:  40.0
Interwave Weekly Out of Hospital Deaths 95% CI:  (27.19635437613577, 49.77732983439054)

When should we consider P1 prevalent?¶

I define any hospitalization on or after 01 December 2020 as being P1 affected, and none before that.

In [1642]:
#### Define Pre and Post P1 Periods Prevalence

P1_date = pd.to_datetime('2020-12-01')

# Sets the new column 'P1' as 1 if the patient was hospitalized during the P1 period or 0 if he'she was hospitalized before P1 was prevalent

df.loc[df['DT_INTERNA'] >= P1_date, 'P1'] = 1

df.loc[df['DT_INTERNA'] < P1_date, 'P1'] = 0

Analysis Section¶

Did NON-COVID SRAGs experience higher/faster in-hospital mortality due to COVID-related hospital overload in Manaus?¶

Use Cox Proportional Hazards to analyse covariates:

  • Age
  • Hospital COVID19 Load
  • Excess Out of Hospital Deaths (a marker of hospital collapse)
  • Comorbidities
  • P1 Periods
Defines the critical Regression Analysis Function¶

Timeline is 28 days from hospital admission
Event is in-hospital death

  1. Runs univariate analysis on each covariate
  2. Selects the ones that reach statistical significance (corrected by Bonferroni for the number of analyses done)
  3. Runs multivariate Cox PH regression on these selected covariates
  4. Plots the Hazard Ratios of covariates in multi regression
In [1643]:
def CoxAnalysis(data,duration_col,event_col,covariates,time, significance_level, formula = None, filters = None):
    
    global cph
    
    cph = CoxPHFitter() # Apparently this makes the variables global instead of local

    t = np.linspace(0, time, time+1) # define the timeline
    
    #### Prepare the dataset for Univariate analysis
    # Removes all records which have missing data for any of the fields analysed
    
    analysis_columns = [duration_col,event_col, *covariates] #unpacks covariates inside the list, essentially concatenating it
    
    data_uv = data.rename(columns={'Corrected_Hosp_Manaus_plus_Queue':'OccupiedBeds'}) \
                .dropna(subset=analysis_columns) # Critically removes records with missing data for field to be analysed
    

    # Initialy an empty summary dataframe
    summary = pd.DataFrame()

    # Run univariate analysis on each one of the covariates given 
    for covariate in covariates:
    
        cph.fit(data_uv, duration_col=duration_col,event_col=event_col, formula=covariate, timeline=t)
        
        summary = summary.append(cph.summary) # append the results of this analysis to the Summary dataframe
        
    ## Bonferroni correction of significance value
    bonferroni = significance_level / len(covariates)
    
    # Creates new column 'UnivariateSignificance' and fills it with bonferroni-corrected threshold used on rows which passed statistical significance
    summary.loc[summary['p'] < bonferroni,'UnivariateSignificance'] = "<{:.3f}".format(round(bonferroni,3))
    
    ## Print Total Number of Records Analysed
    print('\nNumber of entries used in univariate analysis: ',len(data_uv))
    
    ## Print Table of Univariate Results
    print('\nUnivariate Regression Results\n')
    print(summary.to_string())

    #### MultiVariate Analysis with covariates that passed statistical significance
    
    covariates_passed_uv = summary[summary.UnivariateSignificance.notna()].index
    
    #### Prepare the dataset for Multivariate analysis
    # Removes all records which have missing data for any of the fields analysed
    
    analysis_columns = [duration_col,event_col, *covariates_passed_uv] #unpacks covariates inside the list, essentially concatenating it
    
    data_mv = data.rename(columns={'Corrected_Hosp_Manaus_plus_Queue':'OccupiedBeds'}) \
                .dropna(subset=analysis_columns) # Critically removes records with missing data for field to be analysed
    
    ## Creates the linear covariates formula to be passed for CoxPHFitter with only variables that passed univariate analysis
    
    if formula is None:
         
        formula = ' + '.join(covariates_passed_uv) 
    
    else:
        
        formula = formula    


    cph.fit(data_mv, duration_col=duration_col,event_col=event_col, formula=formula, timeline=t)

    ## Print Total Number of Records Analysed
    print('\nNumber of entries used in multivariate analysis: ',len(data_mv))
    
    ## Print Table of

    print('\nMultivariate Regression Results:\n')

    summary_mv = cph.summary
    summary_mv.loc[summary_mv['p'] < significance_level,'MultivariateSignificance'] = "<{:.3f}".format(significance_level)
    
    print(summary_mv.to_string())
    
    ## Print Hazard Ratio Plots
    
    print('\nHazard Ratios for Covariates: \n')
    cph.plot()

Do these results show similar results in Rio Grande do Sul state?¶

In [1658]:
### STEP 3
### Keep only records notified up to sivep_release_offset_weeks before the latest SIVEP release
df_gaucho = df_copy.copy(deep=True) #To be used later if needed
In [1659]:
#### Import Hospital Data for RS
gaucho = pd.read_csv(f'{SIVEP_directory}RS_HospitalData_08042021.csv')
gaucho.Date_Updated = pd.to_datetime(gaucho.Date_Updated)

## These are the columns which will be added up to calculate how many patients in total are receiving hospital treatment for suspected or confirmed COVID
ColumnsHospitalizations = ['Suspected_Adult_ICU',
       'Confirmed_Adult_ICU',
 
       'Suspected_Ped_ICU',
       'Confirmed_Ped_ICU',
 
       'Suspected_Adult_Ward',
       'Confirmed_Adult_Ward',
 
       'Suspected_Ped_Ward',
       'Confirmed_Ped_Ward']

## Originally the imported CSV has one line per Hospital, and each has to be updated on a daily basis. 
# This groups all updates for a given date and sums them by column, getting the total for each category
# and then sums across the line, getting a grande total of beds occupied. 
gaucho_resampled = gaucho.resample('D', on='Date_Updated')[ColumnsHospitalizations].sum().sum(axis=1)

When should we consider P1 prevalent in RS?¶

I define any hospitalization on or after 01 February 2020 as being P1 affected, and none before that.

In [1660]:
#### Define Pre and Post P1 Periods Prevalence

P1_date = pd.to_datetime('2021-02-01')

# Sets the new column 'P1' as 1 if the patient was hospitalized during the P1 period or 0 if he'she was hospitalized before P1 was prevalent

df_gaucho.loc[df_gaucho['DT_INTERNA'] >= P1_date, 'P1'] = 1

df_gaucho.loc[df_gaucho['DT_INTERNA'] < P1_date, 'P1'] = 0

Cut off for SIVEP hospital admission needs to be more recent, as the second wave in RS is still ongoing.
Defined cutoff as 4 weeks later than the Manaus cutoff Moving this data any further forward increase substantially the number of entries for which there are no updates on outcomes,
and this is not the type of censoring that survival analysis typically deals with.

In [1661]:
RS_sivep_analysis_cutoff = sivep_release - timedelta(weeks=sivep_release_offset_weeks - 4)

ax = plt.subplot(111)
df_gaucho[df_gaucho.SG_UF_INTE == 'RS'].resample('D', on='DT_INTERNA')['HOSPITAL'].count().to_frame().reindex(pd.date_range(gaucho_resampled.index.min(),gaucho_resampled.index.max())).plot(style='b.', ax=ax, figsize=(8,4))
ax.set_title('New SRAG Hospital Admissions per Day (SIVEP)\nRio Grande do Sul State')
ax.axvline(P1_date, alpha=0.5, label='P1')
ax.axvline(RS_sivep_analysis_cutoff, alpha=0.5, color='red', label='Analysis Cutoff')
ax.legend().set_visible(True)
plt.show()
In [1662]:
df_gaucho = df_gaucho[df_gaucho['DT_NOTIFIC'] < RS_sivep_analysis_cutoff]
